<br>
If I didn't have my own personal money, I would probably go back to work part time when DS turned 1 because I feel very very strongly that women should have their own money. <br>
<br>
While MamaG's first post, and to some extent her second post bugs me a little, I can see her point of feeling like she has to defend her choice to work. On this board it does seem that staying at home is the norm.  I personally admire those who work and parent because once a mother comes home I would guess that 75% of the time she is a full time mother - meaning without much DH help like in the middle of the night calls. <br>
<br>
But I could see how to MamaG it is relaxing to be that way. Because at home, those demanding on her love her. They give sloppy kisses and sticky hugs. They are thrilled to see you. And gotta say that my dd is usually a perfectly behaved child once DH comes home. Because he isn't worn out by that time of day of the constent pressure of dealing with an almost 3yo. She listens to him better. And She is his responsibility until bedtime. I'm done in by then usually. <br>
<br>
What I think makes staying at home so stressful (IMO) is the fact that most of what we do is unappreciated. It bothers me that DH thinks I've got it easy. Oh it really bothers me. Because I know on some days at work they watch movies and play video games. He points out that he gets up at 5am on the days he works. Ok he has to get up earlier then I USUALLY do (about once a week I'm up by that time). But on hte days he doesn't work (3 on 3 off) he sleeps until at least 10. Today I got to sleep until 7. I am usually up at 6. I would say that on average I'm up before himm, but he refuses to see that. I cook and half the time DD won't eat (thankfully DS will eat anything if he can feed himself). I wash laundry and fold it only to have to do it again the next day. It is rare for anyone to compliment on a clean house, or other things, but at 5am I hear if that laundry isn't done and DH has no socks or undershirt. <br>
<br>
I love my babies, but they don't appreciate my work for them right now. <br>
<br>
There are times when all I feel is wife and mother aka whore and maid. I have been struggling over the past couple of months trying to find something for ME. That is just about me. Maybe the kids can tag along, but I'm doing it FOR ME. And I'm having a hard time finding it and doing it on a regular basis. DH could really help out some more. But he's under the opinion that I don't need help. <br>
<br>
I got excited that I was running errands yesterday BY MY SELF. What would have taken me 2 or 2 1/2 hours only took me an hour! It was thrilling to be alone. To have my body to myself for an hour. And it was in the middle of the day. Sure I didn't go until DS was asleep, but DD was still awake. But see, right now even my breaks out are mostly dependant on how quick they will be or when DS is asleep.  The other night I decided I wanted movie popcorn so I decided to go see a movie (not much of a choice here). I couldn't get DS asleep, but DH for once said he would take him. So I went. And come home to find that DS screamed for 45 minutes. *sigh*That is more crying than DS does during the whole day usually. And I'm not sure the guilt I feel over DS crying is worth the break, even as needed as it was.<br>
<br>
Kim <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#b9a1d0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> sweetpeas mommy</span><br> <span class=usertitle>Unregistered User</span><br>   <font color=#3333ff>(5/1/03 6:39 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=196.topic&index=24>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_sunglasses.gif" align=absmiddle>  split priorities</span><hr size=1> For the record, since &quot;split priorities&quot; was brought up in MamaG's defense of herself and I was the one who said that, I did not imply others had split priorities. What I said was, &quot;For me, not working outside the home means that I don't feel like my priorities are split.&quot;<br>
