Support like that, I could live without.......<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :rolleyes --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/eyes.gif ALT=":rolleyes"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#9fb7df><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=dbc67>DBC67</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Avatar of Reason</span><br>  Posts: 259<br> <font color=#3333ff>(5/1/03 3:18 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=196.topic&index=27>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.rune-stone.net/Pitt/avatar.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_sunglasses.gif" align=absmiddle>  Wrongly accused!</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I was reacting to DBC stating that being at home is so much less stressful than working and that SAHP's have it so much easier..<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Actually, what I said was I had it easier being at work than my wife does being home.  I said it in the context of my job as contrasted to hers and relative to our individual skills at the roles we chose.  I de-stress when I get home by playing with my kids, reading, building with blocks or talking about their day over dinner.  These things however are not what the entire day consists of as a SAHP.  There is getting to school, packing lunches, getting to karate and violin, play dates, making sure enough books were read, art was made, exercise was had, enough milk is in the house, clothes are matched, no one is choking, laundry is wherever it needs to be (floor, hamper, washer, dryer, basket, drawer) dogs got out, cat got in, dishes were loaded or unloaded, and too much TV was not on.  <br>
<br>
There was a commercial once about shaving where you can see it as something you have to do every day, or as something you do for a lifetime, implying that a chore is only a chore if you see it as work.  I know several people that find repetitive tasks and habitual tidiness as rewarding and satisfying.  I am not one such person.  I go into a high pressure job, I am in law school at the same time, I argue all day long and I have more reading to face weekly than most editors plus I am quizzed on the material in ways that carry definite financial consequences.  There are those who would find that daunting and we have lost many who cracked under that type of pressure.  I however thrive and savor it.  I do not kid myself that I would do as well at home and as I said earlier because of the responsibility DW has to loved ones it is a “Way different order of pressure.”  Apples and Oranges really.<br>
<br>
Does this make me bad?  Am I a better person than a SAHP?  Do I think that if I became a single parent I would blow the job and my kids become disenfranchised criminals?  Are women the weaker vessel and must be shackled to the job?<br>
<br>
What I am is suited to the role I am in.  What my wife is is suited to the role she has chosen.  What we are is well matched and happy in our paths.  My wife is not very confrontational.  If she came in to my job she’d last about 8 seconds.  By the same token if I were to do hers we’d all have pink clothes and be eating spaghetti-o’s out of the can.  “From each according to their abilities, to each according to their needs.”  If I were to take a different job we’d have way less money (Lets not kid ourselves here that there is some altruistic reason for working.  We work to get paid.  I get paid enough so that she can work or not as she chooses, the household does not require it.)  <br>
<br>
Society is not holding guns to our heads and saying we must be breadwinner and chaimbermaid each. I kept working because I earned more.  I earn more than 4 out of my 5 siblings.  That’s just common sense.  If she earned more or we earned equally but I was a better SAHP then the choice would be different.  Can she have a career?  If she wants one.  Can she go to school?  I wish she would, but she doesn’t want to right now.  Her choice.  If I lost her and had to do it alone would I curl up and die?  No.  I’d probably be a damn good single parent.  I work very hard, I am semi-intelligent, I don’t just decide on gut instinct; my kids would be cared for and loved and raised to the best of my abilities.  If she wanted things differently, that is up to her to decide.  She can do anything she wants.  Just don’t project onto us some social inequity that isn’t there.<br>
