ll behaved most of the time, then you may find it easier to SAH.  That doesn't mean it is the case for everybody, but the person who does fall into that category shouldn't be attacked.  I work full-time for part of the year, and part-time for the rest.  The less I work, the less stress I have.  The reason for my particular situation is because I only have one child at home, and he is extremely well behaved.  He has his moments, and there are days where I go nuts at home with him, but that kid is a breeze to raise, and if that was my only job, then it would be much less stressful than coming into this office and staring down this pile of audits I need to finish.  Once this next baby comes along, then that may change.  I may find my days at work to be less stressful than my days at home trying to take care of 2 kids and a house, especially if this baby isn't as easy as my first one. <br>
<br>
As for the comment about how people who choose to work shouldn't have kids, I find that judgemental as well.  I work because I have to, but if I didn't have to work, then I would probably at least stay working part-time.  I know part-time isn't the same as choosing to work full-time, but there are a lot of mothers out there who choose to work full-time, and they still do a great job at raising their kids.  First of all, what is the difference between sending a child to daycare because you have to as opposed to doing it by choice?  Either way, the mother will be at work and the child will be in daycare.  I know there are parents out there who are more concerned with climbing the corporate ladder than taking care of their children, but those types of parents wouldn't be much different if they stayed home.  I've seen children of both working and SAH parents who are neglected.  Neither one is better than the other.  Some people just have the types of personalities where they need stimulation outside the home.  I question all the time whether or not I'd be able to tolerate staying home full-time.  I'm just lucky that my career path led me to a job where I can work just part-time, and still make enough to cover daycare.  Some people don't have the part-time option with their jobs, regardless of finances.  Certain jobs just can't cater to anyone who is there less than 40 hours a week.  If a woman has this kind of job, but she doesn't think she would do well as a stay home mom, then the family is better off with her working.  That doesn't make her less of a mother, she is just wired differently.  Besides, people who work by choice don't always just blow this extra money on themselves.  They have college funds for their kids, they have retirement funds so they won't be a burden to their kids in their old age, they can afford extracurricular activities which are good for children and they can afford family vactions in order to provide their kids with positive childhood memories.  As long as the children always come first, then working does not hurt the children.<br>
<br>
With all that being said, I think there are 3 necessary factors that need to be in place in order to have a good balance when one parent works outside the home.  You need a good partner, good daycare and a flexible job that understands family comes first.  I am very fortunate because I have all 3.  My dh and I split all the household chores and child duties.  When I work less, then I do a little more.  If I need to stay late on night, then I know my dh can hold down the fort.  That part also answers the other question about splitting the chores, lol.  I also have an excellent daycare situation.  My son absolutely loves his daycare, and it has been a very positive experience.  I know he is in good hands when I'm gone, and I know he isn't suffering in any way.  I also have a flexible job.  If I get a call saying that my son is sick, then I don't need to ask if I can leave.  I tell them I'm leaving.  I don't need to clear doctor's appointments ahead of time, and if I feel like taking off early because there is a special party or carnival at the daycare, then I just leave.  To be fair to my employer, I sometimes take work home or swing by on the weekend during his naptime in order to make sure things are still getting done.  I am very fortunate that I have all the right tools in place to create a nice work/life balance.  If any one of those 3 factors fell apart, then things would be going a lot differently.<br>
<br>
When it comes to the general subject of WOH vs SAH, then I'll just reiterate that it all depends on the individuals involved.  Finances are usually the driving force in this decision, but it also helps when you look at the people involved.  The reason why I wonder whether or not I'd be able to stay home is because I'm not sure if it fits my personality.  With the exception of cooking, I hate hate hate domestic duties.  If my income was all disposable, then I'd hire someone to clean.  I've done that in the past, and I plan to do that again.  I also need a certain type of stimulation for my mind.  I didn't choose to be an accountant because it is a glamorous job.  I chose to be an accountant because it fits with the way my brain functions.  I'm a real puzzle person, and this was the perfect fit.  It is hard to say whether I'd function well if I didn't have this outlet to allow my brain what it does best.  If my talents lied elsewhere, then maybe I could squeeze that in at home.  A lot of stay home moms like to do crafts.  This suits them well, and it is a perfect fit within their domestic life.  I suck at crafts, and I have no creativity at all.  I'm thankful that Dylan's daycare does all sorts of neat arts and crafts with him because I can't offer him that kind of creativity at home.  For the most part, I work because I have to.  My dh makes good money, but we came into our marriage with a lot of debts because we had to financially struggle in order to make our way through school.  We came from middle class families that made too little to pay for college, but too much to qualify for much in the way of financial aid.  Some of our debts were by choice.  We had a vision of what we wanted to provide for our children.  It was important for us to raise our children in a house, and that this house be in a safe neighborhood with good schools.  It was also important to us to make sure we had safe and reliable vehicles to drive our children around in.  Everyone has different visions of how they want to raise their children, but these things were important to us.  The most important thing here is that Dylan is happy, and he is.  This is our personal story, and other people's circumstances may not fit in here.  This is why people need to consider what is right for them from finances down to personalities, and to make a choice that is right for you.  Just remember that what is right for you may not be right for another.<br>
<br>
Stacey <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#b9a1d0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mamagadfly>MamaGadfly</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 370<br> <font color=#3333ff>(5/2/03 4:43 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=196.topic&index=38>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_sunglasses.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: WM vs SAHM</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Part of support is letting people feel how they want to, and I think your whole post kind of invalidates those who do think it's challenging to stay home as making too much of it.....<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
